of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: nickname from <i>Broz</i>, an old Bavarian word meaning ‘toad’ and, in a figurative sense, ‘showy’.","German: habitational name from any of various places in Brandenburg, Lower Saxony, and Luxembourg called Protz(en).","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Proca</b> or <b>Próca</b>: nickname from Upper Sorbian <i>proca</i>, Lower Sorbian <i>próca</i> ‘trouble, (hard) work’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Prouz was born about 1160, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. He married Jane Joan Basset about 1190. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1216."},"et":{"about 1160–after 1216":"umbes 1160–pärast 1216","1162–1213":"1162–1213","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1199–Male":"1199–Surnud","1191–Male":"1191–Surnud","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1216":"1216","after 1216":"pärast 1216","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1213":"1213","1199":"1199","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","Abt 1191":"umbes 1191","1170":"1170","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","1191":"1191","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berkhamstead, Hertfordshire, , England":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Eastervale, Devonshire, England":"Devon, In